recordings.loc: Skidaway Island, Chatham County, GA USA
recordings.rmk: An interesting call, very similar to the alarm call of Northern Saw-whet Owl, but the spectrogram, which does not show up well on these pages is noticeably different.  For those that follow this arcane stuff, NSWO has a series of distinct harmonics associated with its 'wail'. BAOW fledglings show a sound, which I guess could be consider harmonics, starting and trending well above 5kHz.  The sound itself is in a tight range of approximately 1-1.2kHz. A surprising gap to me.

recordings.loc: Minnesota (near  Houston), Houston County, Minnesota
recordings.rmk: The ascending portion of this call is split into two notes, which isn't common in our area. It was recorded on continuous recording audio/video equipment to monitor captive Great Horned Owls. Odom calls this a scream (alarm), but Bob Pearson calls it a whistle-shriek, and questions if it is indeed an alarm call. It is given somewhat regularly in our area, although the Barred Owls are not near to our captive Great Horned Owls.

recordings.loc: Cook, Skamania County, Washington
recordings.rmk:
Originally a Mystery Recording, thanks to XC contributors [Dan Lane](http://www.xeno-canto.org/contributor/WOEAFQRMUD) and  [Nathan Pieplow](http://www.xeno-canto.org/contributor/EKKJJJRDJY) for helping identify & confirm the species as [Northern Barred Owl](http://www.xeno-canto.org/species/Strix-varia).



**Original post follows**
This owl woke me from sleep in my car when I heard it in my headphones. There was a Great Horned Owl flying around, hootin' it up earlier in the day (around 15:30!), so I know there was one in the area. I'm not familiar enough with owl calls to know that this was a GHO, though, so I thought I'd ask.

I'd upload a longer recording, but really, it was this lone, isolated call, with an hour of silence on either side before the next sound (some leaves falling)

Enjoy the reverb! There are some nice, tall conifers there.

Anyone know?

recordings.loc: Washington (near  Bow), Skagit County, Washington
recordings.rmk:
For the better part of two weeks and continuously throughout the day and night, a male and female Barred Owl were seen and heard frequently.  If unfamiliar, the female has the higher pitched call.  From what I understand these are descendants of other Barred Owls that have been on Samish Island for some time.  This is actually a remarkable duet to hear and of course to experience.

It was just before 5:30 pm when this recording was made on a Zoom H4N.  It was hand held with the cone handle in place.  This is a mature wooded area.

recordings.loc: Suches, Fannin County, Georgia
recordings.rmk: We were on our honeymoon in north Georgia.  We sat on the back porch of our cabin, overlooking the Blue Ridge Mountains and began calling into the woods just after sunset. Not long after, we received our first barred owl response! Then several different groups of barred owls all began responding to us from the trees at many different points around the cabin! Never did we expect to hear so many all at once. We were thrilled and carried on a back-and-forth conversation with these noisy nocturnal predators for nearly an hour, full of hoots, wails and caterwauls.  We took a one minute trim of the recording for submission here; it is completely unedited.

recordings.rmk: I spotted one barred owl roosting in the open (mixed stand of big leaf maple and alder) at a height of 10 feet/3m from the ground.  The bird called several times, made a short flight, and resumed calling.  This is the point where I began recording.  I caught one call from the first bird, and then heard another bird perhaps 30 ft/10 m away begin to call.  I then saw a pair fly, and call in flight; this happened twice that I was able to see.  I apologize for the poor quality of the recording, but hopefully it captures the antiphonal nature of the calls.

About 12 minutes later, a Barred Owl responded, flew within about 25 m of us, and landed on a branch. The owl then flew to a branch about 80 m away, called again (recorded here), then left. recordings.loc: Blake Road, Sidney, Kennebec County, Maine
recordings.rmk:
Previously entered as "unknown" but now identified as a barred owl.  I am leaving the orginal comments below for the sake of completeness. Thank you to everyone for your comments!  --Lance



Unknown sound.  Heard after playing a great horned owl recording.   The sounds continued after I played barred owl, northern saw-whet owl, and long-eared owl recordings.  The source of the sounds moved at least twice during the ~25 minutes that I heard it.

I have heard barred and northern saw-whet owl at this location previously (most recently only about six weeks earlier) but this sound doesn't match any by those species that I've ever heard.  I checked every barred owl recording on Xeno-Canto and in the Cornell Master Set but these vocalizations don't match any of them.  I also checked all the Great Horned Owl and Northern Saw-whet Owl vocalizations in the Cornell Master Set and found nothing that matched.

It's possible that this is not a bird and perhaps a mammal.

Recorded in a wet forest adjacent to agricultural fields.  Sounds of traffic from nearby  interstate 95 are also audible.

Equipment: Sony PCM-M10 recorder and a Sennheiser ME67 microphone.
Modifications to the file: amplified by 10 dB.
